Exercise 2 âï¸

Letâs look at some interesting patterns in the history of LEGO! Weâll be using data from the lego package located data/legosets.rda.

First, letâs look at the average cost of LEGO sets over time. The main variable of interest here is USD_MSRP, or the manufacturerâs suggested retail price in constant dollars.

# data wrangling
lego_average=legosets %>% 
  group_by(Year) %>% 
  summarize(avg_price = mean(USD_MSRP, na.rm = TRUE))

ggplot(data = lego_average, mapping = aes(x = Year, y = avg_price))+
  geom_line()+
  geom_point(color = "red")+
  labs(x="Years",
       y="price USD",
       title ="Average Price of LEGO sets",
       subtitle = "Amount are reported in current USD",
       caption = "Source : LEGO"
       )+ 
   theme_minimal()


Exercise 3 âï¸

Letâs explore how many unique themes LEGO now offers.

theme_counts <- legosets %>%
  count(Theme)

theme_counts %>%
  ggplot(aes(y = Theme, x = n)) +
  geom_col() +    # or geom_bar(stat = "identity") +
  labs(
    title = "Messy Plot",
    x = "Number of Sets",
    y = NULL
  ) +
  theme_minimal()

What is bad/ugly about the plot above?

ANSWERâ There are too much information and itâs hard to read the detail.

Now remake the plot BUT with the improvements.

theme_counts <- legosets %>%
  count(Theme, sort = TRUE) %>% 
  mutate(
    Theme = fct_inorder(Theme, ordered=TRUE)
  )

  
theme_counts %>%
  filter(n>=100) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(y = fct_rev(Theme), x = n)) +
  geom_col() +    # or geom_bar(stat = "identity") +
  labs(
    x = "Number of Sets",
    y = NULL,
    title = 'Improved plot'
  ) +
  theme_minimal()


Exercise 4 âï¸

Now you try, letâs look at how the number of pieces per set has changed over time. Because Duplo sets are much smaller (since theyâre designed for toddlers), we made a special indicator variable for them shown in the code below.

Use an appropriate graph to plot the average number of pieces over time. Have either separate lines or separate plots for the Duplo and Lego categories. Be sure the title, x-axis, and y-axis are properly labeled.

pieces_per_year <- legosets %>%
  # new indicator variable
  mutate(Duplo = ifelse(Theme == "Duplo", "Duplo", "Lego")) %>%
  group_by(Year,Duplo) %>% 
  summarise(avg_piece = mean(Pieces, na.rm = TRUE))

ggplot(data = pieces_per_year, mapping = aes(x = Year, y = avg_piece))+
  geom_line()+
  facet_wrap(~Duplo)+
  geom_point(color = "red")+
  labs(x="Years",
       y="Pieces",
       title ="Average Pieces of LEGO sets",
       subtitle = "Amount are reported in current USD",
       caption = "Source : LEGO"
       )+ 
   theme_minimal()

What trends do you notice in the plots? Are you surprised by the plots?

ANSWERâ I noticed that after the year 1975, both groups have the trend of going upward.Thatâs not a surprising result, and I have the same prediction after year 2020.
